column14: In my opinion, influential change is the change that forces us to rewrite big chunks of code not directly connected with the change reason.

Refactoring for improved readability and code reuse. 

We often "hack" things to get stuff done. Before approaching a next feature, we need to clear up things to avoid future confusion. Thus we refactor things, preparing the field for future work.
User facing bugs, generally due to platform fragmentation (devices, device versions and/or OS versions)

UI/UX: look and feel, usability
Dependency management systems
Breaking changes to system requirements e.g. JDK versions, RAM minimum etc

Promotion of new API methods, demotion (deprecation) of old (but still functional) methods.
Documentation additions/revisions or newly documented workarounds
The influential stuff happens not in code changes, but in design discussions, for example on the issue tracker.

column15: When a project develops further sometimes the developers get a great idea which influences the further development and outcome of the project, the common goal or mindset of the group or individual is to me an important part that gives motivation when it is written down on paper and is clear, this seems a bit to much overlooked at the moment and should be taken into consideration especially for controversial changes and/ or small developers

column15: I suggest that you use "Influential Software Changes" for the name of this study. It took me a while to figure out that "Program" referred to computer programming when initially reading the email.

The example for the "Major structural change" category is bad: the commit merely changes line endings. Although a na√Øve diff shows the whole file as changed, in reality nothing changed in the file at all. (That said, I believe it is important that the line endings in all files of a project be consistent.)

more focued on smaller projects, see below
column15: These are all in reference to large, "mega-project" style projects. Most developers work in smaller teams, on much smaller projects and don't get so involved in controversies. Even most open source projects are still handled by a very small number of people and what we're seeing now is that sometimes people implement features which become path dependent and then they defend them only because it would wreck so many dependencies of the project, despite their not being well thought out. The good thing is you can just fork a project and re-write it to your specs.
